I can see why this kiosk is getting bad reviews. It's the food and presentation.  Went here on a Sunday night and they were among the few locations open. Kudos for that. There was no line behind me, but I did have to repeat my order a number of times, and inquire whether the dining room in Ogilvie was open or not (it was).  The prices online are slightly cheaper than ordering in person, not sure why.  I ordered a chicken sandwich, something that's been talked about the past few months and... I don't see what the big deal is. It was served lukewarm and there was way too much breading for my comfort level, two or three bites worth of no actual chicken. The mayo was slobbered on. The pickles were distinct but ironically an unwelcome presence as they lacked the contrasting texture a Chick-Fil-A or Wendy's chicken sandwich would provide.  Fries were similarly lukewarm and hard. That's a bad thing, and the Popeyes-branded ketchup didn't do much to fix it.  With no sweet tea left, the Coke I was served (with completely melted ice) had come with a taped lid... why? Don't you think putting one's fingers on the center of all the lids to apply tape would cross contaminate with the food? Certainly defeats the purpose.  It was not a good experience, but hopefully it's not forever. Until they get their inventory and management systems in check, consider another Popeyes in the meantime.
